2) PLATFORM OVERVIEW & ARCHITECTURE
   • ServiceNow is an aPaaS platform used across IT, HR, Finance, Security, etc.
• Helps automate manual, repeatable workflows.
• Not just a ticketing tool — a full enterprise workflow platform.

ARCHITECTURE
• ServiceNow uses a **multi-instance architecture**:
  - Each customer gets its own application stack + DB.
  - No co-mingling of data with other customers.
  - Higher isolation, better control over updates & performance.

• Backups:
  - ServiceNow performs **weekly full backups** and **daily differential backups**.
  - Retention windows depend on customer subscription; exact # of stored backups
    is not fixed (no longer “4 weekly + 6 daily”).
  - Backups are used for restoration & cloning.

• High availability:
  - Redundant data centers.
  - Traffic failover during outages.


NOTE:->

MULTI-INSTANCE:
- Each customer gets their own separate, independent instance
- Completely isolated environment with separate database and servers
- Higher cost but greater customization flexibility
- One customer's data is completely isolated from others
- Example: Company A has Instance 1, Company B has Instance 2

MULTI-TENANT:
- Single instance serves multiple customers
- Data is logically separated using tenant IDs or row-level security
- Lower cost due to shared resources
- All customers share same application and infrastructure
- Easier to deploy updates (everyone gets them simultaneously)

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
3) SECURITY & AUTHENTICATION
   SUPPORTED AUTH METHODS
• Local Database (username/password stored in User table)
• SAML 2.0 SSO (Okta, Azure AD, etc.)
• LDAP integration
• OAuth 2.0 (commonly used for API & Mobile authentication)
• Digest Token (legacy; rarely used now)
• Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA):
  - TOTP (Google Authenticator, Microsoft Authenticator)
  - **FIDO2 / WebAuthn Passkeys (2024+)**
  - Email/SMS (depending on org policies)

ROLE-BASED ACCESS
• User → Group → Role hierarchy.
• Best practice: Assign roles to **groups**, not users.
• Base roles: admin, itil, approver_user, catalog_admin.
• Self-service users (no roles) can:
  - Submit requests/incidents
  - Access portal & catalog

• Impersonation: Admins can view system as another user.


NOTE:->

1) LOCAL DB (USERNAME/PASSWORD):
   - Username and password stored in ServiceNow database
   - Simplest method, no external systems needed
   - Risk: passwords exposed if instance compromised

2) SSO - SAML 2.0 (e.g., Okta):
   - User logs in via external identity provider (Okta, Azure AD, etc.)
   - ServiceNow trusts the provider's verification
   - No password shared with ServiceNow
   - Best for: enterprise with multiple apps

3) LDAP:
   - Authenticates against company's Active Directory
   - ServiceNow queries LDAP to validate credentials
   - Syncs with on-premise directory
   - Best for: organizations with Active Directory

4) OAUTH 2.0 (CLIENT_ID + SECRET):
   - Third-party apps request access to ServiceNow
   - Client_id identifies the app; client_secret is app's password
   - Tokens granted instead of passwords
   - Best for: API integrations, third-party access

5) DIGEST TOKEN:
   - HTTP authentication for API calls
   - Password sent as hashed digest (not plain text)
   - Safer than basic auth; used for REST integrations

6) MULTI-FACTOR AUTHENTICATION (MFA) (e.g., Google Authenticator):
   - Adds second security layer
   - User enters password + code from authenticator app
   - Can combine with any auth method (SSO + MFA, LDAP + MFA, etc.)
   - Best for: high-security environments

QUICK RULE:
- Internal users = Local DB or LDAP
- Enterprise = SSO (SAML)
- API access = OAuth or Digest Token
- Extra security = Add MFA on top

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
4) USER INTERFACES (2025 UPDATE)

ServiceNow now has **three major UX experiences**:

1. **Next Experience (Unified Navigation)** — NEW DEFAULT UI  
   - Introduced in San Diego release.  
   - Replaces legacy UI16 as primary UI.  
   - Provides workspaces, modern navigation, improved theming.

2. **Workspaces (Next Experience Workspaces)**
   - Agent Workspace
   - CSM Workspace
   - ITSM Workspace / Service Operations Workspace (2023–2025)

3. **Service Portal**
   - Modern self-service UI for end users.  
   - Still widely used.

⚠ Legacy UI update:
• UI15 is obsolete.  
• UI16 exists but is **not the recommended long-term UI**.  
• Many organizations migrate to **Next Experience**.

SUPPORTED BROWSERS
• Chrome, Edge, Firefox, Safari (latest versions recommended).

MOBILE APPS
-----------------------------------
• Now Mobile — for employees to submit requests, tasks, approvals.
• Mobile Agent — for fulfillers handling incidents/requests on the go.
• Mobile Onboarding — for HR onboarding processes.

2025 Update:
• All mobile apps now use the **ServiceNow Mobile Platform**, with enhanced
  offline support and deep-linking features.


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
--> UI EVOLUTION (important update)
   - Historically UI15 and UI16 were common toggleable UI versions. Since then,
     ServiceNow introduced the "Now/Next Experience" and workspace concepts (e.g.,
     Service Operations Workspace) and ongoing UI improvements across releases.
   - UI16 still exists in many instances, but **the recommended UI or experience may
     change with releases** — admins should follow release notes and the Now Experience
     guidance because elements (edge, layout, widgets) may evolve. :contentReference[oaicite:14]{index=14}

